    "Henceforth, we always operate in the following setting:Setting 1.",
    "Fix W, T, r, d, D ∈ N + with 1 ≤ r < W. We fix a continuous activation function σ: R → R which is either a bounded Lipschitz or the ReLU activation function.",
    "We assume there is a constant M > 0 such that A (t) ij < M for all t, i, j throughout the LoRA training.",
    "Main Upper-Bound on LoRA Generalization GapOur main theorem is the following randomized generalization bound.Theorem 1 (LoRA Sample Complexity: Upper-Bound).",
    "In setting 1: for every failure probability 0 < δ ≤ 1, the following holds with probability at least 1 -δG ≤ 4 min 1, √ q 6 √ A √ N + 8 log(2/(1 - √ 1 -δ) N where A = (cT + 1) log(2R + 2R 0), R = M ν 2r log(2W/ϵ) and R 0 = ∥θ pre ∥ ∞.Remark 2 (Symmetry in the Upper Bound -Randomizing B vs. A)."
